<collectionCode id="0090AE5FDD1E5A37FBB6FDC8C8A8CCC8" box="[1071,1166,615,642]" country="France" httpUri="http://biocol.org/urn:lsid:biocol.org:col:34988" lsid="urn:lsid:biocol.org:col:34988" name="Museum National d'Histoire Naturelle" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">MNHN</collectionCode>
.F. 
<accessionNumber id="79D2AB79DD1E5A37FB3FFDC8C92ECCC8" box="[1190,1288,615,642]" httpUri="http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/nucleotide/A31529" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">A31529</accessionNumber>
</materialsCitation>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="663E369ADD1E5A37FF7AFD06CD92CC89" blockId="28.[227,436,681,707]" box="[227,436,681,707]" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">
<heading id="3D7681F6DD1E5A37FF7AFD06CD92CC89" bold="true" box="[227,436,681,707]" fontSize="11" level="3" pageId="28" pageNumber="29" reason="3">
<emphasis id="54F5EA88DD1E5A37FF7AFD06CD92CC89" bold="true" box="[227,436,681,707]" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">Shell description</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="663E369ADD1E5A37FF7AFD78CF2CCDEB" blockId="28.[226,1437,727,930]" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">
Medium-sized shell (SL max.: 
<quantity id="A1799B7FDD1E5A37FDC2FD77CEFDCCB8" box="[603,731,728,754]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.943" pageId="28" pageNumber="29" unit="mm" value="29.43">29.43 mm</quantity>
). Early spire whorls conical to convex, of low to medium height. Later spire whorls conical in outline, with convex, smooth sutural ramp. Subsutural flexure moderately deep, strongly curved, moderately asymmetrical (
<figureCitation id="FEBA2A1FDD1E5A37FC20FCB1C83BCD72" box="[953,1053,798,824]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="61.[227,270,1647,1673]" captionTargetBox="[227,1437,912,1604]" captionTargetId="figure-374@61.[227,1437,912,1604]" captionTargetPageId="61" captionText="Fig. 40. Examples of subsutural flexures. A. Conus (Lautoconus) eschewegi Pereira da Costa, 1866 (MNHN.F.A82976). B. Conus (Lautoconus) ictini sp. nov. (AMPG(IV) 3719). C. Conus (Lautoconus) sp. 1 (MNHN.F.A82982). D. Conus (Lautoconus) sp. 2 (AMPG(IV) 3756). E. Conus (Lautoconus) sp. 3 (MNHN.F.A83012). F. Conus (Lautoconus) cf. baldichieri Borson, 1820 (MNHN.F.A83013). G. Conus (Lautoconus) lauriatragei sp. nov. (MNHN.F.A83014). H. Conus (Lautoconus) damianakisi sp. nov. (AMPG(IV) 3802). I. Conus (Lautoconus) sp. 4 (MNHN.F.A83015). J. Conus (Lautoconus) sp. 5 (AMPG(IV) 3861). K. Conus (Stephanoconus) cf. taurinensis Bellardi &amp; Michelotti, 1841 (AMPG(IV) 3808). L. Conus (Stephanoconus) moissettei sp. nov. (MNHN.F.A83071). M. Conus davolii sp. nov. (MNHN.F.A83091). N. Conus fuscocingulatus Hörnes, 1851 (AMPG(IV) 3858). O. Conus (Plagioconus) elatus Michelotti, 1847 (AMPG(IV) 3862). P. Conus (Plagioconus) sp. (AMPG(IV) 3890). Q. Conus (Plagioconus) sp. (AMPG(IV) 3898). R. Conus (Plagioconus) aquensis d’Orbigny, 1852 (AMPG(IV) 3907). Not to scale." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6484351" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6484351/files/figure.png" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">Fig. 40I</figureCitation>
). Shoulder smooth at early spire whorls, slightly angulated at later spire whorls. Maximum diameter below shoulder. Last whorl conical, slightly widened. Aperture narrow, straight, widening towards slightly twisted fasciole. Shell smooth, except for two faded spiral cords near fasciole.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="663E369ADD1E5A37FF7AFC67CE3ECDA8" blockId="28.[227,536,968,995]" box="[227,536,968,995]" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">
<heading id="3D7681F6DD1E5A37FF7AFC67CE3ECDA8" bold="true" box="[227,536,968,995]" fontSize="11" level="3" pageId="28" pageNumber="29" reason="3">
<emphasis id="54F5EA88DD1E5A37FF7AFC67CE3ECDA8" bold="true" box="[227,536,968,995]" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">Colour pattern variation</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="663E369ADD1E5A37FF7AFC58CE1ECB4D" blockId="28.[226,1437,1015,1288]" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">The colour pattern on the spire whorls consists of irregular blotches. The colour pattern on the last whorl consists of two levels of colouration. The first one consists of fluorescent blotches. The second level consists of spirally arranged irregular rows of fluorescent dashes, interrupted by non-fluorescent tents. The tents can be either as small as dots, or small non-fluorescent dashes, or can be axially wide enough to unite with other tents and create an axial non-fluorescent area. The resulting pattern is variable and depends on the number of tents, as well as on the size of those tents. The Cretan specimen shows an axial unification of the tents, while the Turkish specimen displays a spiral unification of the tents, in the middle part of the last whorl.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="663E369ADD1E5A37FF7AFA80CF2CCB9C" blockId="28.[226,1436,1326,1494]" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">
We noticed that the specimen from Apomarma (
<collectionCode id="0090AE5FDD1E5A37FC96FA81CF48CB03" box="[783,878,1326,1353]" country="France" httpUri="http://biocol.org/urn:lsid:biocol.org:col:34988" lsid="urn:lsid:biocol.org:col:34988" name="Museum National d'Histoire Naturelle" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">MNHN</collectionCode>
.F. 
<accessionNumber id="79D2AB79DD1E5A37FC1FFA81CFC1CB03" box="[902,999,1326,1353]" httpUri="http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/nucleotide/A83015" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">A83015</accessionNumber>
) had different grades of erosion, with non-fluorescent areas being more resistant to erosion, than those being previously with colour patterns (see 
<figureCitation id="FEBA2A1FDD1E5A37FE81FADACD59CBC5" box="[280,383,1397,1423]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="29.[227,270,1893,1919]" captionTargetBox="[224,1434,721,1857]" captionTargetId="figure-177@29.[224,1434,721,1857]" captionTargetPageId="29" captionText="Fig. 17. Conus (Lautoconus) sp. 4 from the Tortonian of Crete (Greece) and the Piacenzian of Antakya (Turkey) (figure altered after Caze 2010), displayed under natural (A3–A5) and UV light. A. Specimen MNHN.F.A83015, Apomarma, displaying different grades of erosion (A3 box zoomed to A4). B. Specimen MNHN.F.A31529, Samandag (photo by Caze 2010). Scale bars: A1–A3, A5–B3 = 1 cm; A4 = 500 μm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6484301" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6484301/files/figure.png" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">Fig. 17A</figureCitation>
<quantity id="A1799B7FDD1E5A37FEE6FADACD8DCBC5" box="[383,427,1397,1423]" metricMagnitude="-1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.016" pageId="28" pageNumber="29" unit="in" value="4.0">
<figureCitation id="FEBA2A1FDD1E5A37FEE6FADACDA8CBC5" box="[383,398,1397,1423]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="11.[227,270,1930,1956]" captionTargetBox="[351,1311,302,1897]" captionTargetId="figure-11@11.[351,1311,302,1897]" captionTargetPageId="11" captionText="Fig. 4. Conus (Lautoconus) ictini sp. nov. from the Tortonian of Crete (Greece) on apertural, abapertural and apical views, under natural (A1, A3, A4, B1) and UV light. A. Holotype AMPG(IV) 3719, Tefeli. B. Paratype AMPG(IV) 3720, Tefeli. C. Paratype AMPG(IV) 3718, Tefeli. D. Specimen AMPG(IV) 3716, Achladhia. Scale bar = 1 cm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6484271" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6484271/files/figure.png" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">4</figureCitation>
in
</quantity>
comparison to the right side of 
<figureCitation id="FEBA2A1FDD1E5A37FC80FADACFA5CBC5" box="[793,899,1397,1423]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="29.[227,270,1893,1919]" captionTargetBox="[224,1434,721,1857]" captionTargetId="figure-177@29.[224,1434,721,1857]" captionTargetPageId="29" captionText="Fig. 17. Conus (Lautoconus) sp. 4 from the Tortonian of Crete (Greece) and the Piacenzian of Antakya (Turkey) (figure altered after Caze 2010), displayed under natural (A3–A5) and UV light. A. Specimen MNHN.F.A83015, Apomarma, displaying different grades of erosion (A3 box zoomed to A4). B. Specimen MNHN.F.A31529, Samandag (photo by Caze 2010). Scale bars: A1–A3, A5–B3 = 1 cm; A4 = 500 μm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6484301" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6484301/files/figure.png" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">Fig. 17A</figureCitation>
<figureCitation id="FEBA2A1FDD1E5A37FC1AFADACFB7CBC5" box="[899,913,1397,1423]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="8.[227,270,2002,2028]" captionTargetBox="[227,1437,1374,1958]" captionTargetId="figure-189@8.[227,1437,1374,1958]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="Fig. 3. Elements constituting the colour pattern of Conus (Lautoconus) eschewegi Pereira da Costa, 1866 (MNHN.F.A82974) from the Tortonian of Crete (Greece). Scale bar = 1 cm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6484269" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6484269/files/figure.png" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">3</figureCitation>
, where the shell is not so eroded). This might indicate that the substance enclosed in the shell structure, which is responsible for the pigments, is more prone to erosion than the non-pigmented areas.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="2E9B6511DD1E5A36FF7AFA52CF52CC2C" lastPageId="29" lastPageNumber="30" pageId="28" pageNumber="29" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="663E369ADD1E5A37FF7AFA52CD73C85D" blockId="28.[227,341,1533,1559]" box="[227,341,1533,1559]" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">
<heading id="3D7681F6DD1E5A37FF7AFA52CD73C85D" bold="true" box="[227,341,1533,1559]" fontSize="11" level="3" pageId="28" pageNumber="29" reason="3">
<emphasis id="54F5EA88DD1E5A37FF7AFA52CD73C85D" bold="true" box="[227,341,1533,1559]" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">Remarks</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="663E369ADD1E5A37FF7AF984CFCCC644" blockId="28.[226,1439,1579,2063]" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">
This species is placed in 
<taxonomicName id="A1814D19DD1E5A37FD8DF983CEBDC80F" authorityName="Monterosato" authorityYear="1923" box="[532,667,1580,1605]" class="Gastropoda" family="Conidae" genus="Lautoconus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neogastropoda" pageId="28" pageNumber="29" phylum="Mollusca" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="54F5EA88DD1E5A37FD8DF983CEBDC80F" box="[532,667,1580,1605]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">Lautoconus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, as it has smooth early spire whorls and a convex sutural ramp. The Pliocene Turkish specimen identified by 
<bibRefCitation id="02104B6BDD1E5A37FD76F9E1CF5BC822" author="Caze B." box="[751,893,1614,1640]" pageId="28" pageNumber="29" refId="ref28783" refString="Caze B. 2010. Interet systematique de l'etude des motifs colores residuels chez les mollusques du Cenozoique d'Europe. PhD Thesis, MNHN, Paris." type="book" year="2010">Caze (2010)</bibRefCitation>
as 
<taxonomicName id="A1814D19DD1E5A37FC3BF9E0C8B6C823" authority="" box="[930,1168,1614,1641]" class="Gastropoda" family="Conidae" genus="Conus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neogastropoda" pageId="28" pageNumber="29" phylum="Mollusca" rank="subGenus" subGenus="Chelyconus">
<emphasis id="54F5EA88DD1E5A37FC3BF9E0CFCBC823" box="[930,1005,1615,1641]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">Conus</emphasis>
(
<emphasis id="54F5EA88DD1E5A37FC64F9E1C8A0C822" box="[1021,1158,1614,1640]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">Chelyconus</emphasis>
)
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis id="54F5EA88DD1E5A37FB0FF9E1C887C822" box="[1174,1185,1614,1640]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">?</emphasis>
<taxonomicName id="A1814D19DD1E5A37FB39F9E1C9BDC822" authority="Brocchi, 1814" authorityName="Brocchi" authorityYear="1814" box="[1184,1435,1614,1640]" class="Gastropoda" family="Conidae" genus="Conus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neogastropoda" pageId="28" pageNumber="29" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="pyrula">
<emphasis id="54F5EA88DD1E5A37FB39F9E1C8D7C822" box="[1184,1265,1614,1640]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">pyrula</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation id="02104B6BDD1E5A37FB6FF9E1C9BDC822" author="Brocchi G." box="[1270,1435,1614,1640]" pageId="28" pageNumber="29" refId="ref28745" refString="Brocchi G. 1814. Conchiologia fossile subapennina, con osservazioni geologiche sugli Apennini e sul suolo adiacente. Stamperia reale, Milano. https: // doi. org / 10.5962 / bhl. title. 11569" type="book" year="1814">Brocchi, 1814</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
and the Cretan specimen of 
<taxonomicName id="A1814D19DD1E5A37FDA0F9DDCF0CC8C6" authority="" authorityName="Monterosato" authorityYear="1923" box="[569,810,1650,1676]" class="Gastropoda" family="Conidae" genus="Conus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neogastropoda" pageId="28" pageNumber="29" phylum="Mollusca" rank="subGenus" subGenus="Lautoconus">
<emphasis id="54F5EA88DD1E5A37FDA0F9DDCEA2C8C6" box="[569,644,1650,1676]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">Conus</emphasis>
(
<emphasis id="54F5EA88DD1E5A37FD0EF9DDCF06C8C1" box="[663,800,1650,1675]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">Lautoconus</emphasis>
)
</taxonomicName>
sp. 4 share smooth and convex spire whorls with a slightly angulated shoulder (
<figureCitation id="FEBA2A1FDD1E5A37FDA8F93ACEA3C8E5" box="[561,645,1685,1711]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="29.[227,270,1893,1919]" captionTargetBox="[224,1434,721,1857]" captionTargetId="figure-177@29.[224,1434,721,1857]" captionTargetPageId="29" captionText="Fig. 17. Conus (Lautoconus) sp. 4 from the Tortonian of Crete (Greece) and the Piacenzian of Antakya (Turkey) (figure altered after Caze 2010), displayed under natural (A3–A5) and UV light. A. Specimen MNHN.F.A83015, Apomarma, displaying different grades of erosion (A3 box zoomed to A4). B. Specimen MNHN.F.A31529, Samandag (photo by Caze 2010). Scale bars: A1–A3, A5–B3 = 1 cm; A4 = 500 μm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6484301" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6484301/files/figure.png" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">Fig. 17</figureCitation>
) and have a similar colour pattern. Thus, they very likely belong to the same species. The typical Pliocene 
<taxonomicName id="A1814D19DD1E5A37FD2BF917CF74C898" authorityName="Brocchi" authorityYear="1814" box="[690,850,1720,1746]" class="Gastropoda" family="Conidae" genus="Conus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neogastropoda" pageId="28" pageNumber="29" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="pyrula">
<emphasis id="54F5EA88DD1E5A37FD2BF917CF74C898" box="[690,850,1720,1746]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">Conus pyrula</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
bears a colour pattern of axially arranged stripes. 
<taxonomicName id="A1814D19DD1E5A37FF7DF974CDF5C8BF" authority="" authorityName="Monterosato" authorityYear="1923" box="[228,467,1755,1781]" class="Gastropoda" family="Conidae" genus="Conus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neogastropoda" pageId="28" pageNumber="29" phylum="Mollusca" rank="subGenus" subGenus="Lautoconus">
<emphasis id="54F5EA88DD1E5A37FF7DF974CD09C8BF" box="[228,303,1755,1781]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">Conus</emphasis>
(
<emphasis id="54F5EA88DD1E5A37FED9F973CDEFC8BF" box="[320,457,1756,1781]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">Lautoconus</emphasis>
)
</taxonomicName>
sp. 4 differs from the Paratethyan species of 
<taxonomicName id="A1814D19DD1E5A37FC6FF974CDAEC953" authority="(Harzhauser &amp; Landau 2016)" baseAuthorityName="Harzhauser &amp; Landau" baseAuthorityYear="2016" class="Gastropoda" family="Conidae" genus="Conus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neogastropoda" pageId="28" pageNumber="29" phylum="Mollusca" rank="subGenus" subGenus="Lautoconus">
<emphasis id="54F5EA88DD1E5A37FC6FF974C867C8BF" box="[1014,1089,1755,1781]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">Conus</emphasis>
(
<emphasis id="54F5EA88DD1E5A37FBCBF973C8FDC8BF" box="[1106,1243,1756,1781]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">Lautoconus</emphasis>
) (
<bibRefCitation id="02104B6BDD1E5A37FB6CF974CDA6C953" author="Harzhauser M. &amp; Landau B." pageId="28" pageNumber="29" pagination="1 - 178" refId="ref29682" refString="Harzhauser M. &amp; Landau B. 2016. A revision of the Neogene Conidae and Conorbidae (Gastropoda) of the Paratethys Sea. Zootaxa 4210 (1): 1 - 178. https: // doi. org / 10.11646 / zootaxa. 4210.1.1" type="journal article" year="2016">Harzhauser &amp; Landau 2016</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
in the presence of tents in its colour pattern. 
<taxonomicName id="A1814D19DD1E5A37FC02F951C8ACC953" authority="" authorityName="Monterosato" authorityYear="1923" box="[923,1162,1790,1817]" class="Gastropoda" family="Conidae" genus="Conus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neogastropoda" pageId="28" pageNumber="29" phylum="Mollusca" rank="subGenus" subGenus="Lautoconus">
<emphasis id="54F5EA88DD1E5A37FC02F951CFC0C952" box="[923,998,1790,1816]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">Conus</emphasis>
(
<emphasis id="54F5EA88DD1E5A37FC6EF950C8A6C952" box="[1015,1152,1791,1816]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">Lautoconus</emphasis>
)
</taxonomicName>
sp. 5 (see below) has a similar colour pattern of tents, but it differs morphologically from this species in the smooth outline of the spire whorls and the olive-like morphological outline. As such, we consider these specimens as two separate species. Unfortunately, in lacking more specimens with similar morphological characteristics and colour pattern, we do not name this species. 
<taxonomicName id="A1814D19DD1E5A37FCADF824C805C9EF" authority="" authorityName="Monterosato" authorityYear="1923" box="[820,1059,1931,1957]" class="Gastropoda" family="Conidae" genus="Conus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neogastropoda" pageId="28" pageNumber="29" phylum="Mollusca" rank="subGenus" subGenus="Lautoconus">
<emphasis id="54F5EA88DD1E5A37FCADF824CF59C9EF" box="[820,895,1931,1957]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">Conus</emphasis>
(
<emphasis id="54F5EA88DD1E5A37FC09F824C83FC9EE" box="[912,1049,1931,1956]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">Lautoconus</emphasis>
)
</taxonomicName>
sp. 4 has a very common shell outline and is not easily distinguishable from other species without the help of UV light. The colour pattern is also reminiscent of extant species of 
<taxonomicName id="A1814D19DD1E5A37FC8FF87EC82EC9A1" authority="" authorityName="Monterosato" authorityYear="1923" box="[790,1032,2001,2027]" class="Gastropoda" family="Conidae" genus="Conus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neogastropoda" pageId="28" pageNumber="29" phylum="Mollusca" rank="subGenus" subGenus="Lautoconus">
<emphasis id="54F5EA88DD1E5A37FC8FF87ECF47C9A1" box="[790,865,2001,2027]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">Conus</emphasis>
(
<emphasis id="54F5EA88DD1E5A37FCEDF87DCFDBC9A1" box="[884,1021,2002,2027]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">Lautoconus</emphasis>
)
</taxonomicName>
, such as the West African species 
<taxonomicName id="A1814D19DD1E5A37FF7CF85ACECFC644" authority="Rolan, 1986" authorityName="Rolan" authorityYear="1986" box="[229,745,2036,2063]" class="Gastropoda" family="Conidae" genus="Conus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neogastropoda" pageId="28" pageNumber="29" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="saragasae" subGenus="Lautoconus">
<emphasis id="54F5EA88DD1E5A37FF7CF85ACD16C645" box="[229,304,2037,2063]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">Conus</emphasis>
(
<emphasis id="54F5EA88DD1E5A37FEA6F85ACDEEC644" box="[319,456,2037,2062]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">Lautoconus</emphasis>
) 
<emphasis id="54F5EA88DD1E5A37FE40F85ACE74C644" box="[473,594,2037,2062]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">saragasae</emphasis>
Rolán, 1986
</taxonomicName>
(
<bibRefCitation id="02104B6BDD1E5A37FD6EF85BCFFBC644" author="Tenorio M. J. &amp; Abalde S. &amp; Pardos-Blas J. R. &amp; Zardoya R." box="[759,989,2036,2063]" pageId="28" pageNumber="29" pagination="1 - 89" refId="ref32106" refString="Tenorio M. J., Abalde S., Pardos-Blas J. R. &amp; Zardoya R. 2020. Taxonomic revision of West African cone snails (Gastropoda: Conidae) based upon mitogenomic studies: implications for conservation. European Journal of Taxonomy (663): 1 - 89. https: // doi. org / 10.5852 / ejt. 2020.663" type="journal article" year="2020">
Tenorio 
<emphasis id="54F5EA88DD1E5A37FCC2F85ACFA9C644" box="[859,911,2036,2062]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">et al</emphasis>
. 2020
</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="663E369ADD1F5A36FF7AFE80CE2FCF9E" blockId="29.[225,1436,303,468]" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">
The morphological outline of 
<taxonomicName id="A1814D19DD1F5A36FDFEFE80CF79CF03" authority="" authorityName="Monterosato" authorityYear="1923" box="[615,863,303,329]" class="Gastropoda" family="Conidae" genus="Conus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neogastropoda" pageId="29" pageNumber="30" phylum="Mollusca" rank="subGenus" subGenus="Lautoconus">
<emphasis id="54F5EA88DD1F5A36FDFEFE80CE94CF03" box="[615,690,303,329]" italics="true" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">Conus</emphasis>
(
<emphasis id="54F5EA88DD1F5A36FD55FE9FCF73CF03" box="[716,853,304,329]" italics="true" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">Lautoconus</emphasis>
)
</taxonomicName>
sp. 4 can be compared with several 
<taxonomicName id="A1814D19DD1F5A36FAC8FE80CD8ECF26" authority="" authorityName="Morch" authorityYear="1852" class="Gastropoda" family="Conidae" genus="Conus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neogastropoda" pageId="29" pageNumber="30" phylum="Mollusca" rank="subGenus" subGenus="Stephanoconus">
<emphasis id="54F5EA88DD1F5A36FAC8FE80C9BACF03" box="[1361,1436,303,329]" italics="true" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">Conus</emphasis>
(
<emphasis id="54F5EA88DD1F5A36FF74FEFECDB9CF21" box="[237,415,337,363]" italics="true" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">Stephanoconus</emphasis>
)
</taxonomicName>
species discussed in this work (e.g., 
<taxonomicName id="A1814D19DD1F5A36FCCDFEFDCD83CFC4" authority="Bellardi &amp; Michelotti, 1841" authorityName="Bellardi &amp; Michelotti" authorityYear="1841" class="Gastropoda" family="Conidae" genus="Conus" isUncertain="true" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neogastropoda" pageId="29" pageNumber="30" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="taurinensis" subGenus="Stephanoconus">
<emphasis id="54F5EA88DD1F5A36FCCDFEFDCFB9CF26" box="[852,927,338,364]" italics="true" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">Conus</emphasis>
(
<emphasis id="54F5EA88DD1F5A36FC29FEFEC844CF21" box="[944,1122,337,363]" italics="true" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">Stephanoconus</emphasis>
) cf. 
<emphasis id="54F5EA88DD1F5A36FB0EFEFDC93FCF21" box="[1175,1305,338,363]" italics="true" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">taurinensis</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation id="02104B6BDD1F5A36FAB9FEFECD83CFC4" author="Bellardi L. &amp; Michelotti G." pageId="29" pageNumber="30" refId="ref28689" refString="Bellardi L. &amp; Michelotti G. 1841. Saggio orittographico sulla classe dei gasteropodi fossili dei terreni terziarii del Piemonte. Memorie della Reale Accademia delle Scienze di Torino, Torino." type="book" year="1841">Bellardi &amp; Michelotti, 1841</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="A1814D19DD1F5A36FE40FEDACE02CFC5" authorityName="Eschewegi Pereira da Costa" authorityYear="1866" box="[473,548,373,399]" class="Gastropoda" family="Conidae" genus="Conus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neogastropoda" pageId="29" pageNumber="30" phylum="Mollusca" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="54F5EA88DD1F5A36FE40FEDACE02CFC5" box="[473,548,373,399]" italics="true" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">Conus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicName id="A1814D19DD1F5A36FDB3FEDACF9BCFC4" authority="Psarras &amp; Merle &amp; Koskeridou, 2022" authorityName="Psarras &amp; Merle &amp; Koskeridou" authorityYear="2022" box="[554,957,372,399]" class="Gastropoda" family="Conidae" genus="Conus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neogastropoda" pageId="29" pageNumber="30" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="moissettei" status="sp. nov." subGenus="Stephanoconus">
<emphasis id="54F5EA88DD1F5A36FDB3FEDACE53CFC5" box="[554,629,373,399]" italics="true" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">Conus</emphasis>
(
<emphasis id="54F5EA88DD1F5A36FD1FFEDBCF1ECFC4" box="[646,824,372,398]" italics="true" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">Stephanoconus</emphasis>
) 
<emphasis id="54F5EA88DD1F5A36FCD1FEDACF9BCFC4" box="[840,957,373,398]" italics="true" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">moissettei</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel id="4FC657F3DD1F5A36FC58FEDAC838CFC5" box="[961,1054,373,399]" pageId="29" pageNumber="30" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
). Both species, however, possess the tuberculate early spire whorls, lacking in 
<taxonomicName id="A1814D19DD1F5A36FD71FE38CFF0CFFB" authority="" authorityName="Monterosato" authorityYear="1923" box="[744,982,407,433]" class="Gastropoda" family="Conidae" genus="Conus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neogastropoda" pageId="29" pageNumber="30" phylum="Mollusca" rank="subGenus" subGenus="Lautoconus">
<emphasis id="54F5EA88DD1F5A36FD71FE38CF15CFFB" box="[744,819,407,433]" italics="true" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">Conus</emphasis>
(
<emphasis id="54F5EA88DD1F5A36FCDDFE37CFEBCFFB" box="[836,973,408,433]" italics="true" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">Lautoconus</emphasis>
)
</taxonomicName>
sp. 4. Furthermore, their colour pattern is not comprised of tents.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="663E369ADD1F5A36FF7AFE55CDFCCC5E" blockId="29.[227,474,506,532]" box="[227,474,506,532]" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">
<heading id="3D7681F6DD1F5A36FF7AFE55CDFCCC5E" bold="true" box="[227,474,506,532]" fontSize="11" level="3" pageId="29" pageNumber="30" reason="3">
